A.2. Theoretical Analysis of L JD Definition A.1 (Jeffreys Divergence) . We define the symmetric objective function L JD (θ) as the sum of the Forward and Reverse Kullback-Leibler divergences (Jeffreys, 1948) : Proof. For brevity, we omit the conditioning on the input x and output y. Substituting the definition of confidence score c θ (y|x) = q θ (y|x) p(y|x) into the expanded form of L JD , we derive:

L JD (p, q θ ) = L KL (p||q θ ) + L (R)KL (q θ ||p) ( 16

)

L JD (p, q θ ) = L KL (p∥q θ ) + L KL (q θ ∥p) ( 17

) = E y∼p(•|x) log p(y|x) q θ (y|x) + E y∼q θ (•|x) log q θ (y|x) p(y|x) ( 18

) = E y∼p(•|x) log p(y|x) q θ (y|x) + |V| i=1 q θ (y i |x) p(y i |x) p(y i |x) log q θ (y i |x) p(y i |x) ( 19

) = E y∼p(•|x) log p(y|x) q θ (y|x) + q θ (y|x) p(y|x) log q θ (y|x) p(y|x) ( 20

) = E p log 1 c θ + c θ log c θ ( 21

) = E p (c θ -1) log c θ g(c θ ) (22)

To analyze the optimization landscape, we decompose the objective into the per-class loss function g(c θ ). We treat the teacher probability p as a static scaling factor and analyze the behavior of g(c θ ) in three distinct regimes:

Case 1: Overconfidence (c θ → ∞). As the student assigns excessive probability mass relative to the teacher, the term is dominated by c θ log c θ . Unlike JSD (which is linear), JD applies a severe penalty to hallucinations:

lim c θ →∞ g(c θ ) ≈ c θ log c θ (Super-Linear Penalty)

Case 2: Underconfidence (c θ → 0). As the student fails to capture the teacher's probability mass, the term is dominated by -log c θ . Unlike JSD (which is bounded), JD enforces an infinite penalty for missed recall:

lim c θ →0 g(c θ ) ≈ ∞ (Unbounded Tail Sensitivity)

Case 3: Perfect Alignment (c θ = 1). When the student perfectly matches the teacher (q θ = p), the loss vanishes, confirming c θ = 1 as the global minimum: g(1) = (1 -1) log 1 = 0

Thus, L JD enforces a convex basin that prevents the student from drifting into extreme regions, strictly driving the confidence score towards the equilibrium at c θ = 1.
